.TH "ELEMENT.SETHTMLUNSAFE" "3JS" "August 19, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Element.setHTMLUnsafe \- Element: setHTMLUnsafe() method
.SH SYNOPSIS
.RS
.PP
\f[B]Warning:\f[R] This method parses its input as HTML, writing the
result into the DOM.
APIs like this are known as injection sinks, and are potentially a
vector for cross\-site\-scripting (XSS) attacks, if the input originally
came from an attacker.
.PP
You can mitigate this risk by always passing \f[CR]TrustedHTML\f[R]
objects instead of strings and enforcing trusted types.
See Security considerations for more information.
.RE
.RS
.PP
\f[B]Note:\f[R] \f[CR]Element.setHTML()\f[R] should almost always be
used instead of this method \(em on browsers where it is supported \(em
as it always removes XSS\-unsafe HTML entities.
.RE
.PP
The \f[B]\f[CB]setHTMLUnsafe()\f[B]\f[R] method of the
\f[CR]Element\f[R] interface is used to parse HTML input into a
\f[CR]DocumentFragment\f[R], optionally filtering out unwanted elements
and attributes, and those that don\(cqt belong in the context, and then
using it to replace the element\(cqs subtree in the DOM.
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
setHTMLUnsafe(input)
setHTMLUnsafe(input, options)
.EE
.SS Parameters
.TP
\f[B]input\f[R]
A \f[CR]TrustedHTML\f[R] instance or string defining HTML to be parsed.
.TP
\f[B]options\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
An options object with the following optional parameters:
.RS
.TP
\f[B]sanitizer\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
A \f[CR]Sanitizer\f[R] or \f[CR]SanitizerConfig\f[R] object that defines
what elements of the input will be allowed or removed.
This can also be a string with the value \f[CR]\(dqdefault\(dq\f[R],
which applies a \f[CR]Sanitizer\f[R] with the default (XSS\-safe)
configuration.
If not specified, no sanitizer is used.
.RS
.PP
Note that generally a \f[CR]Sanitizer\f[R] is expected to be more
efficient than a \f[CR]SanitizerConfig\f[R] if the configuration is to
reused.
.RE
.RE
.SS Return value
None (\f[CR]undefined\f[R]).
.SS Exceptions
.TP
\f[B]TypeError\f[R]
This is thrown if:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]input\f[R] is passed a string when Trusted Types are enforced by a
CSP and no default policy is defined.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]options.sanitizer\f[R] is passed a:
.RS 2
.IP \(bu 2
value that is not a \f[CR]Sanitizer\f[R], \f[CR]SanitizerConfig\f[R], or
string.
.IP \(bu 2
non\-normalized \f[CR]SanitizerConfig\f[R] (one that includes both
\(lqallowed\(rq and \(lqremoved\(rq configuration settings).
.IP \(bu 2
string that does not have the value \f[CR]\(dqdefault\(dq\f[R].
.RE
.RE
.SH DESCRIPTION
The \f[B]\f[CB]setHTMLUnsafe()\f[B]\f[R] method is used to parse an HTML
input into a \f[CR]DocumentFragment\f[R], optionally sanitizing it of
unwanted elements and attributes, and discarding elements that the HTML
specification doesn\(cqt allow in the target element (such as
\f[CR]<li>\f[R] inside a \f[CR]<div>\f[R]).
The \f[CR]DocumentFragment\f[R] is then used to replace the element\(cqs
subtree in the DOM.
.PP
Unlike with \f[CR]Element.innerHTML\f[R], declarative shadow roots in
the input will be parsed into the DOM.
If the string of HTML defines more than one declarative shadow root in a
particular shadow host then only the first \f[CR]ShadowRoot\f[R] is
created \(em subsequent declarations are parsed as \f[CR]<template>\f[R]
elements within that shadow root.
.PP
\f[CR]setHTMLUnsafe()\f[R] doesn\(cqt perform any sanitization by
default.
If no sanitizer is passed as a parameter, all HTML entities in the input
will be injected.
It is therefore potentially even less safe that
\f[CR]Element.innerHTML\f[R], which disables \f[CR]<script>\f[R]
execution when parsing.
.SS Security considerations
The suffix \(lqUnsafe\(rq in the method name indicates that it does not
enforce removal of all XSS\-unsafe HTML entities (unlike
\f[CR]Element.setHTML()\f[R]).
While it can do so if used with an appropriate sanitizer, it doesn\(cqt
have to use an effective sanitizer, or any sanitizer at all!
The method is therefore a possible vector for Cross\-site\-scripting
(XSS) attacks, where potentially unsafe strings provided by a user are
injected into the DOM without first being sanitized.
.PP
You should mitigate this risk by always passing \f[CR]TrustedHTML\f[R]
objects instead of strings, and enforcing trusted types using the
\f[CR]require\-trusted\-types\-for\f[R] CSP directive.
This ensures that the input is passed through a transformation function,
which has the chance to sanitize the input to remove potentially
dangerous markup (such as \f[CR]<script>\f[R] elements and event handler
attributes), before it is injected.
.PP
Using \f[CR]TrustedHTML\f[R] makes it possible to audit and check that
sanitization code is effective in just a few places, rather than
scattered across all your injection sinks.
You should not have to pass a sanitizer to the method when using
\f[CR]TrustedHTML\f[R].
.PP
If for any reason you can\(cqt use \f[CR]TrustedHTML\f[R] (or even
better, \f[CR]setHTML()\f[R]) then the next safest option is to use
\f[CR]setHTMLUnsafe()\f[R] with the XSS\-safe default
\f[CR]Sanitizer\f[R].
.SS When should \f[CR]setHTMLUnsafe()\f[R] be used?
\f[CR]setHTMLUnsafe()\f[R] should almost never be used if
\f[CR]Element.setHTML()\f[R] is available, because there are very few
(if any) cases where user\-provided HTML input should need to include
XSS\-unsafe elements.
Not only is \f[CR]setHTML()\f[R] safe, but it avoids having to consider
trusted types.
.PP
Using \f[CR]setHTMLUnsafe()\f[R] might be appropriate if:
.IP \(bu 2
You can\(cqt use \f[CR]setHTML()\f[R] or trusted types (for whatever
reason) and you want to have the safest possible filtering.
In this case you might use \f[CR]setHTMLUnsafe()\f[R] with the default
\f[CR]Sanitizer\f[R] to filter all XSS\-unsafe elements.
.IP \(bu 2
You can\(cqt use \f[CR]setHTML()\f[R] and the input might contain
declarative shadow roots, so you can\(cqt use
\f[CR]Element.innerHTML\f[R].
.IP \(bu 2
You have an edge case where you have to allow HTML input that includes a
known set of unsafe HTML entities.
.RS 2
.PP
You can\(cqt use \f[CR]setHTML()\f[R] in this case, because it strips
all unsafe entities.
You could use \f[CR]setHTMLUnsafe()\f[R] without a sanitizer or
\f[CR]innerHTML\f[R], but that would allow all unsafe entities.
.PP
A better option here is to call \f[CR]setHTMLUnsafe()\f[R] with a
sanitizer that allows just those dangerous elements and attributes we
actually need.
While this is still unsafe, it is safer than allowing all of them.
.RE
.PP
For the last point, consider a situation where your code relies on being
able to use unsafe \f[CR]onclick\f[R] handlers.
The following code shows the effect of the different methods and
sanitizers for this case.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] target = document.querySelector(\(dq#target\(dq);

\f[B]const\f[R] input = \(dq<img src=x onclick=alert(\(aqonclick\(aq) onerror=alert(\(aqonerror\(aq)>\(dq;

\f[I]// Safe \- removes all XSS\-unsafe entities.\f[R]
target.setHTML(input);

\f[I]// Removes no event handler attributes\f[R]
target.setHTMLUnsafe(input);
target.innerHTML = input;

\f[I]// Safe \- removes all XSS\-unsafe entities.\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] configSafe = \f[B]new\f[R] Sanitizer();
target.setHTMLUnsafe(input, { sanitizer: configSafe });

\f[I]// Removes all XSS\-unsafe entities except \(gaonclick\(ga\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] configLessSafe = \f[B]new\f[R] Sanitizer();
config.allowAttribute(\(dqonclick\(dq);
target.setHTMLUnsafe(input, { sanitizer: configLessSafe });
.EE
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS setHTMLUnsafe() with Trusted Types
To mitigate the risk of XSS, we\(cqll first create a
\f[CR]TrustedHTML\f[R] object from the string containing the HTML, and
then pass that object to \f[CR]setHTMLUnsafe()\f[R].
Since trusted types are not yet supported on all browsers, we define the
trusted types tinyfill.
This acts as a transparent replacement for the trusted types JavaScript
API:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]if\f[R] (\f[B]typeof\f[R] trustedTypes === \(dqundefined\(dq)
  trustedTypes = { createPolicy: (n, rules) \f[B]=>\f[R] rules };
.EE
.PP
Next we create a \f[CR]TrustedTypePolicy\f[R] that defines a
\f[CR]createHTML()\f[R] for transforming an input string into
\f[CR]TrustedHTML\f[R] instances.
Commonly implementations of \f[CR]createHTML()\f[R] use a library such
as \c
.UR https://github.com/cure53/DOMPurify
DOMPurify
.UE \c
\ to sanitize the input as shown below:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] policy = trustedTypes.createPolicy(\(dqmy\-policy\(dq, {
  createHTML: (input) \f[B]=>\f[R] DOMPurify.sanitize(input),
});
.EE
.PP
Then we use this \f[CR]policy\f[R] object to create a
\f[CR]TrustedHTML\f[R] object from the potentially unsafe input string:
.IP
.EX
\f[I]// The potentially malicious string\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] untrustedString = \(dqabc <script>alert(1)<\(dq + \(dq/script> def\(dq;
\f[I]// Create a TrustedHTML instance using the policy\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] trustedHTML = policy.createHTML(untrustedString);
.EE
.PP
Now that we have \f[CR]trustedHTML\f[R], the code below shows how you
can use it with \f[CR]setHTMLUnsafe()\f[R].
The input has been through the transformation function, so we don\(cqt
pass a sanitizer to the method.
.IP
.EX
\f[I]// Get the target Element with id \(dqtarget\(dq\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] target = document.getElementById(\(dqtarget\(dq);

\f[I]// setHTMLUnsafe() with no sanitizer\f[R]
target.setHTMLUnsafe(trustedHTML);
.EE
.SS Using setHTMLUnsafe() without Trusted Types
This example demonstrates the case where we aren\(cqt using trusted
types, so we\(cqll be passing sanitizer arguments.
.PP
The code creates an untrusted string and shows a number of ways a
sanitizer can be passed to the method.
.IP
.EX
\f[I]// The potentially malicious string\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] untrustedString = \(dqabc <script>alert(1)<\(dq + \(dq/script> def\(dq;

\f[I]// Get the target Element with id \(dqtarget\(dq\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] target = document.getElementById(\(dqtarget\(dq);

\f[I]// Define custom Sanitizer and use in setHTMLUnsafe()\f[R]
\f[I]// This allows only elements: div, p, button, script\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] sanitizer1 = \f[B]new\f[R] Sanitizer({
  elements: [\(dqdiv\(dq, \(dqp\(dq, \(dqbutton\(dq, \(dqscript\(dq],
});
target.setHTMLUnsafe(untrustedString, { sanitizer: sanitizer1 });

\f[I]// Define custom SanitizerConfig within setHTMLUnsafe()\f[R]
\f[I]// Removes the <script> element but allows other potentially unsafe entities.\f[R]
target.setHTMLUnsafe(untrustedString, {
  sanitizer: { removeElements: [\(dqscript\(dq] },
});
.EE
.SS \f[CR]setHTMLUnsafe()\f[R] live example
This example provides a \(lqlive\(rq demonstration of the method when
called with different sanitizers.
The code defines buttons that you can click to inject a string of HTML.
One button injects the HTML without sanitizing it at all, and the second
uses a custom sanitizer that allows \f[CR]<script>\f[R] elements but not
other unsafe items.
The original string and injected HTML are logged so you can inspect the
results in each case.
.RS
.PP
\f[B]Note:\f[R] Because we want to show how the sanitizer argument is
used, the following code injects a string rather than a trusted type.
You should not do this in production code.
.RE
.SS HTML
The HTML defines two \f[CR]<button>\f[R] elements for calling the method
with different sanitizers, another button to reset the example, and a
\f[CR]<div>\f[R] element to inject the string into.
.IP
.EX
<\f[B]button\f[R] id=\(dqbuttonNoSanitizer\(dq type=\(dqbutton\(dq>None</\f[B]button\f[R]>
<\f[B]button\f[R] id=\(dqbuttonAllowScript\(dq type=\(dqbutton\(dq>allowScript</\f[B]button\f[R]>

<\f[B]button\f[R] id=\(dqreload\(dq type=\(dqbutton\(dq>Reload</\f[B]button\f[R]>
<\f[B]div\f[R] id=\(dqtarget\(dq>Original content of target element</\f[B]div\f[R]>
.EE
.SS JavaScript
First we define the string to sanitize, which will be the same for all
cases.
This contains the \f[CR]<script>\f[R] element and the \f[CR]onclick\f[R]
handler, both of which are considered XSS\-unsafe.
We also define the handler for the reload button.
.IP
.EX
\f[I]// Define unsafe string of HTML\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] unsanitizedString = \(ga
  <div>
    <p>This is a paragraph. <button onclick=\(dqalert(\(aqYou clicked the button!\(aq)\(dq>Click me</button></p>
    <script src=\(dqpath/to/a/module.js\(dq type=\(dqmodule\(dq><script>
  </div>
\(ga;

\f[B]const\f[R] reload = document.querySelector(\(dq#reload\(dq);
reload.addEventListener(\(dqclick\(dq, () \f[B]=>\f[R] document.location.reload());
.EE
.PP
Next we define the click handler for the button that sets the HTML with
no sanitizer.
Generally we would expect the method to drop elements in the string that
aren\(cqt allowed in the context (such as table\-specific elements in a
\f[CR]<div>\f[R] element), but otherwise match the input string.
In this case the strings should match.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] buttonNoSanitizer = document.querySelector(\(dq#buttonNoSanitizer\(dq);
buttonNoSanitizer.addEventListener(\(dqclick\(dq, () \f[B]=>\f[R] {
  \f[I]// Set unsafe HTML without specifying a sanitizer\f[R]
  target.setHTMLUnsafe(unsanitizedString);

  \f[I]// Log HTML before sanitization and after being injected\f[R]
  logElement.textContent =
    \(dqNo sanitizer: string should be injected without filtering\(rsn\(rsn\(dq;
  log(\(ga\(rsnunsanitized: ${unsanitizedString}\(ga);
  log(\(ga\(rsnsanitized: ${target.innerHTML}\(ga);
});
.EE
.PP
The next click handler sets the target HTML using a custom sanitizer
that allows only \f[CR]<div>\f[R], \f[CR]<p>\f[R], and
\f[CR]<script>\f[R] elements.
Note that because we\(cqre using the \f[CR]setHTMLUnsafe()\f[R] method,
\f[CR]<script>\f[R] are not removed!
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] allowScriptButton = document.querySelector(\(dq#buttonAllowScript\(dq);
allowScriptButton.addEventListener(\(dqclick\(dq, () \f[B]=>\f[R] {
  \f[I]// Set the content of the element using a custom sanitizer\f[R]
  \f[B]const\f[R] sanitizer1 = \f[B]new\f[R] Sanitizer({
    elements: [\(dqdiv\(dq, \(dqp\(dq, \(dqscript\(dq],
  });
  target.setHTMLUnsafe(unsanitizedString, { sanitizer: sanitizer1 });

  \f[I]// Log HTML before sanitization and after being injected\f[R]
  logElement.textContent = \(dqSanitizer: {elements: [\(aqdiv\(aq, \(aqp\(aq, \(aqscript\(aq]}\(rsn\(dq;
  log(\(ga\(rsnunsanitized: ${unsanitizedString}\(ga);
  log(\(ga\(rsnsanitized: ${target.innerHTML}\(ga);
});
.EE
.SS Results
Click the \(lqNone\(rq and \(lqallowScript\(rq buttons to see the
effects of no sanitizer and a custom sanitizer, respectively.
.PP
When you click the \(lqNone\(rq button, you should see that the input
and output match, as no sanitizer is applied.
When you click the \(lqallowScript\(rq button the \f[CR]<script>\f[R]
element is still present, but the \f[CR]<button>\f[R] element is
removed.
With this approach you can create safe HTML, but you aren\(cqt forced
to.
.SH SEE ALSO
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]ShadowRoot.setHTMLUnsafe()\f[R]
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]Element.innerHTML\f[R]
.IP \(bu 2
